**NoUI API Conventions**

& Service Contract Definitions

DERP Proof of Concept --- Stream S3 Deliverable

  ---------------------------- ------------------------------------------
  **Document**                 noui-api-conventions

  **Version**                  1.0 (Stream S3, Session 1)

  **Status**                   Draft --- Provisional contracts

  **Authority**                ARCHITECTURE_REFERENCE.md, ADR-001--007

  **Audience**                 All streams (S1--S5)
  ---------------------------- ------------------------------------------

1\. Base URL Structure and Versioning

All NoUI services expose RESTful HTTP APIs under a versioned base path.
The version prefix ensures backward compatibility when breaking changes
are introduced in future releases.

1.1 URL Pattern

> {scheme}://{host}:{port}/api/v{major}/{resource}

For the DERP POC, the three services run on separate ports within the
Kubernetes cluster:

  --------------------- ----------------------- -------------- --------------
  **Service**           **Internal DNS**        **Port**       **Base Path**

  Data Connector        connector.noui.svc      8081           /api/v1

  Intelligence          intelligence.noui.svc   8082           /api/v1

  Workspace             workspace.noui.svc      8083           /api/v1
  --------------------- ----------------------- -------------- --------------

1.2 Versioning Policy

The POC uses v1 for all endpoints. The version number increments only on
breaking changes to request/response schemas. Non-breaking additions
(new optional fields, new endpoints) do not require a version bump. The
version applies at the service level, not per-endpoint. All endpoints
within a service share the same version.

2\. Resource Naming Conventions

All resource names use lowercase, hyphenated plurals. Path parameters
use camelCase identifiers matching domain model field names.

2.1 URL Patterns by Operation Type

  ---------------- ------------------------------------ ---------------------------
  **Pattern**      **Example**                          **Semantics**

  Collection       GET /api/v1/members                  List resources (paginated)

  Instance         GET /api/v1/members/{id}             Retrieve single resource

  Sub-resource     GET /api/v1/members/{id}/salary      Related collection

  Detail variant   GET                                  Full record set (lazy load)
                   /api/v1/members/{id}/salary/detail   

  Action           POST /api/v1/eligibility/evaluate    Non-CRUD operation (verb)

  Calculation      POST /api/v1/benefit/calculate       Deterministic computation
  ---------------- ------------------------------------ ---------------------------

2.2 Naming Rules

-   Resource nouns are plural: /members, /beneficiaries, /contributions

-   Path parameters use member ID, not member_id or memberId in the URL
    itself: /members/{id}

-   Query parameters use camelCase:
    ?retirementDate=2026-04-01&includeTrace=true

-   Action endpoints use verb form: /evaluate, /calculate, /compose

-   No trailing slashes. Requests to /members/ should 301 redirect to
    /members

-   No file extensions in URLs. Content type negotiation via Accept
    header

3\. Request and Response Format

3.1 Content Type

All requests and responses use application/json with UTF-8 encoding. The
Content-Type header must be present on all requests with a body. The
Accept header should be application/json for all requests.

3.2 Standard Response Envelope

All successful responses follow a consistent envelope structure. The
envelope provides metadata alongside the payload so clients can always
rely on the same top-level fields.

> {
>
> \"data\": { \... }, // The primary response payload
>
> \"meta\": {
>
> \"requestId\": \"uuid\", // Unique request identifier for tracing
>
> \"timestamp\": \"ISO-8601\", // Server timestamp of response
>
> \"service\": \"connector\", // Originating service name
>
> \"version\": \"v1\", // API version that served the request
>
> \"degradationLevel\": 0 // Current system degradation level (ADR-007)
>
> }
>
> }

The degradationLevel field in every response enables the frontend to
display appropriate status indicators without polling a separate health
endpoint. Level 0 is normal operation; levels 1--5 correspond to the
degradation hierarchy defined in ADR-007.

3.3 Collection Response with Pagination

> {
>
> \"data\": \[ \... \], // Array of resources
>
> \"pagination\": {
>
> \"total\": 10000, // Total matching resources
>
> \"limit\": 50, // Page size
>
> \"offset\": 0, // Current offset
>
> \"hasMore\": true // Whether more pages exist
>
> },
>
> \"meta\": { \... }
>
> }

Default page size is 50. Maximum page size is 200. Clients request
pagination via query parameters: ?limit=50&offset=100. For the POC, most
sub-resource collections (salary records, employment history) are small
enough to return in full. Pagination is implemented for member search
and transaction log queries.

3.4 Date and Time Format

-   All dates: ISO 8601 format, YYYY-MM-DD (e.g., 2026-04-01)

-   All timestamps: ISO 8601 with timezone, YYYY-MM-DDTHH:MM:SSZ (e.g.,
    2026-04-01T14:30:00Z)

-   All monetary values: string with exactly two decimal places (e.g.,
    \"5432.17\"), never floating point

-   All percentages: decimal number (e.g., 0.03 for 3%), never
    pre-multiplied

-   All service credit durations: object with years and months as
    integers (e.g., { \"years\": 28, \"months\": 9 })

4\. Error Response Format

All error responses use a consistent structure regardless of which
service produces the error. This allows the frontend to implement a
single error-handling path.

4.1 Error Envelope

> {
>
> \"error\": {
>
> \"code\": \"MEMBER_NOT_FOUND\", // Machine-readable error code
>
> \"message\": \"No member found with ID 12345\", // Human-readable
> message
>
> \"details\": { \... }, // Optional structured details
>
> \"source\": {
>
> \"service\": \"connector\", // Service that produced the error
>
> \"endpoint\": \"/api/v1/members/12345\" // Endpoint that failed
>
> }
>
> },
>
> \"meta\": {
>
> \"requestId\": \"uuid\",
>
> \"timestamp\": \"ISO-8601\"
>
> }
>
> }

4.2 HTTP Status Code Usage

  ---------- ------------------------ -------------------------------------
  **Code**   **Meaning**              **When Used**

  200        OK                       Successful GET or POST calculation

  201        Created                  Successful POST creating a resource

  400        Bad Request              Malformed JSON, missing required
                                      fields, invalid date format

  404        Not Found                Member ID, DRO ID, or case ID does
                                      not exist

  422        Unprocessable Entity     Valid JSON but business rule
                                      violation (e.g., not eligible)

  500        Internal Server Error    Unexpected failure in service logic

  502        Bad Gateway              Downstream service unavailable
                                      (Intelligence calling Connector)

  503        Service Unavailable      Service starting up or in degraded
                                      state
  ---------- ------------------------ -------------------------------------

4.3 Standard Error Codes

Each service defines error codes within its namespace. The code field
uses SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE with a service prefix for cross-service
errors.

  ----------------------------- --------------------- -----------------------
  **Error Code**                **HTTP Status**       **Description**

  MEMBER_NOT_FOUND              404                   Member ID not in
                                                      database

  INVALID_RETIREMENT_DATE       400                   Date in past or invalid
                                                      format

  NOT_ELIGIBLE                  422                   Member does not meet
                                                      criteria

  RULE_EVALUATION_FAILED        500                   Rule engine internal
                                                      error

  CONNECTOR_UNAVAILABLE         502                   Intelligence cannot
                                                      reach Connector

  CALCULATION_PRECISION_ERROR   500                   Intermediate result
                                                      overflow

  MISSING_SALARY_DATA           422                   Insufficient salary
                                                      history for AMS

  DRO_NOT_FOUND                 404                   No DRO record for
                                                      member

  AI_SERVICE_UNAVAILABLE        200 (degraded)        Tier 3 composition fell
                                                      back
  ----------------------------- --------------------- -----------------------

5\. Health Check Pattern

Every service exposes two health endpoints outside the versioned API
path. These endpoints are consumed by Kubernetes liveness and readiness
probes, and by the system-wide degradation monitoring.

5.1 Endpoints

  ---------------------- --------------- ---------------------------------
  **Endpoint**           **Probe Type**  **Purpose**

  GET /healthz           Liveness        Is the process alive? Returns 200
                                         if the HTTP server is responding.

  GET /readyz            Readiness       Can the service handle requests?
                                         Checks database connectivity
                                         (Connector), rule loader status
                                         (Intelligence), downstream
                                         reachability (Workspace).
  ---------------------- --------------- ---------------------------------

5.2 Health Response Schema

> {
>
> \"status\": \"healthy\" \| \"degraded\" \| \"unhealthy\",
>
> \"service\": \"connector\",
>
> \"version\": \"1.0.0\",
>
> \"uptime\": \"2h34m12s\",
>
> \"checks\": {
>
> \"database\": { \"status\": \"healthy\", \"latency\": \"2ms\" },
>
> \"rules\": { \"status\": \"healthy\", \"rulesLoaded\": 52 },
>
> \"downstream\": {
>
> \"connector\": { \"status\": \"healthy\", \"latency\": \"5ms\" }
>
> }
>
> }
>
> }

The checks object varies by service. The Connector checks database
connectivity. The Intelligence service checks rule loader status and
Connector reachability. The Workspace service checks both Intelligence
and Connector reachability plus AI service availability (which may be
degraded without affecting overall readiness).

6\. Structured Logging

All services emit structured JSON logs. Every log entry includes the
request ID for distributed tracing across service boundaries.

6.1 Log Fields

  --------------- ---------------- ---------------------------------------
  **Field**       **Type**         **Description**

  timestamp       ISO-8601         When the event occurred

  level           string           DEBUG, INFO, WARN, ERROR

  requestId       UUID             Propagated via X-Request-ID header

  service         string           connector, intelligence, workspace

  method          string           HTTP method

  path            string           Request path (with IDs masked in
                                   production)

  statusCode      integer          HTTP response status

  duration        string           Request processing time (e.g., 12ms)

  memberId        string           Member ID when applicable (masked in
                                   production logs)
  --------------- ---------------- ---------------------------------------

6.2 Request ID Propagation

The frontend generates a UUID for each user action and passes it as the
X-Request-ID header. Each service propagates this header to downstream
calls. If no X-Request-ID is present, the first service in the chain
generates one. This enables end-to-end tracing from the user's click
through all service interactions back to the database query.

7\. Calculation Trace Format

The calculation trace is the foundation of Phase 1 (Transparent)
operation. Every benefit calculation, eligibility determination, and
payment option computation returns a trace object that shows every
input, formula, intermediate result, and final output. This is not
optional metadata---it is a core contract that the frontend depends on
for rendering the BenefitCalculationPanel.

7.1 Trace Structure

> {
>
> \"traceId\": \"uuid\",
>
> \"calculationType\": \"benefit\" \| \"eligibility\" \|
> \"paymentOptions\" \| \"dro\",
>
> \"memberId\": \"12345\",
>
> \"retirementDate\": \"2026-04-01\",
>
> \"timestamp\": \"ISO-8601\",
>
> \"steps\": \[
>
> {
>
> \"stepNumber\": 1,
>
> \"label\": \"Determine Tier\",
>
> \"ruleId\": \"MEMBERSHIP-001\",
>
> \"sourceReference\": \"RMC 18-403.5(a)\",
>
> \"inputs\": { \"hireDate\": \"1997-06-15\" },
>
> \"formula\": \"hireDate \< 2004-09-01 → Tier 1\",
>
> \"result\": \"Tier 1\",
>
> \"notes\": \"Hired before September 1, 2004\"
>
> },
>
> \...
>
> \],
>
> \"finalResult\": {
>
> \"grossBenefit\": \"4312.50\",
>
> \"reduction\": \"0.00\",
>
> \"netBenefit\": \"4312.50\",
>
> \"retirementType\": \"Rule of 75\"
>
> }
>
> }

Every step references its governing rule ID and the statutory source
provision. The frontend renders each step as a row in the calculation
worksheet, enabling the demo's "show your work" capability. Steps are
ordered by execution sequence, and the step chain must be
reproducible---given the same inputs, the same steps produce the same
results.

8\. Cross-Service Communication

Services communicate via synchronous HTTP calls within the Kubernetes
cluster. The Intelligence service calls the Connector to fetch member
data before evaluating rules. The Workspace service calls both
Intelligence and Connector to assemble workspace definitions.

8.1 Service Dependency Graph

-   Frontend → Workspace → Intelligence → Connector → PostgreSQL

-   Frontend → Connector (direct, for data display components)

-   Frontend → Intelligence (direct, for calculation requests)

-   Workspace → Claude API (Tier 3 only, optional, with fallback)

The frontend may call any service directly. The Workspace service
orchestrates calls when composing a complete workspace. Each service is
independently deployable and testable---the Connector can be tested with
only the database, and the Intelligence service can be tested with
mocked Connector responses.

8.2 Timeout and Retry Policy

  ---------------------- --------------- ---------------- ----------------
  **Call Path**          **Timeout**     **Retries**      **Fallback**

  Connector → Database   5 seconds       1 retry, 100ms   Level 4
                                         delay            degradation

  Intelligence →         10 seconds      1 retry, 200ms   502 error
  Connector                              delay            

  Workspace →            15 seconds      No retry         502 error
  Intelligence                                            

  Workspace → Claude API 5 seconds       No retry         Tier 2 fallback
  ---------------------- --------------- ---------------- ----------------

